-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Exodus — Part 3 (Chapters 21–30)
-- 3 difficulties × 10 chapters = 160 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 30
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 50
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 80
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 21–25 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 21 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 21, 'kids', 1, 'After how many years was a Hebrew servant to be set free?', 'After six years of service, he went free in the seventh year', 'After ten years', 'After one year', 'He was never freed', 'a', 'Exodus 21:2 — "If thou buy an Hebrew servant, six years he shall serve: and in the seventh he shall go out free for nothing."'),
('Exodus', 21, 'kids', 2, 'What could a servant do if he loved his master and did not want to leave?', 'His master would bring him to the door and pierce his ear with an awl, and he would serve forever', 'He had to leave anyway', 'He would become the master', 'He would be punished', 'a', 'Exodus 21:5-6 — "And if the servant shall plainly say, I love my master, my wife, and my children; I will not go out free: Then his master shall... bore his ear through with an aul; and he shall serve him for ever."'),
('Exodus', 21, 'kids', 3, 'What famous rule about fairness does this chapter contain?', '"Eye for eye, tooth for tooth" — the punishment should match the harm done', '"First come, first served"', '"Finders keepers"', '"Might makes right"', 'a', 'Exodus 21:24 — "Eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 21, 'teens', 1, 'What protection did God give to servants who were injured by their masters?', 'If a master knocked out a servant''s tooth or destroyed his eye, the servant was to go free as compensation', 'The master paid a fine to the government', 'The servant received no compensation', 'The master was imprisoned', 'a', 'Exodus 21:26-27 — "And if a man smite the eye of his servant, or the eye of his maid, that it perish; he shall let him go free for his eye''s sake. And if he smite out his manservant''s tooth, or his maidservant''s tooth; he shall let him go free for his tooth''s sake."'),
('Exodus', 21, 'teens', 2, 'What happened if an ox gored a person to death?', 'The ox was stoned, but if the owner knew the ox was dangerous and did not keep it penned, the owner could also be put to death', 'The ox was forgiven', 'Nothing happened to the owner', 'The ox was sold to someone else', 'a', 'Exodus 21:28-29 — "If an ox gore a man or a woman, that they die: then the ox shall be surely stoned... But if the ox were wont to push with his horn in time past, and it hath been testified to his owner, and he hath not kept him in... the owner also shall be put to death."'),
('Exodus', 21, 'teens', 3, 'What did the law say about someone who kidnapped another person?', 'He that stealeth a man, and selleth him, or if he be found in his hand, shall surely be put to death', 'He must return the person and pay a fine', 'He is given a warning', 'He must serve the person he kidnapped', 'a', 'Exodus 21:16 — "And he that stealeth a man, and selleth him, or if he be found in his hand, he shall surely be put to death."'),
('Exodus', 21, 'teens', 4, 'What was the law regarding a pregnant woman injured during a fight?', 'If she had a miscarriage but no further harm, the offender paid a fine; but if there was further harm, the lex talionis applied: life for life, eye for eye', 'There was no law about this', 'The woman''s family decided', 'Only fines were possible', 'a', 'Exodus 21:22-25 — "If men strive, and hurt a woman with child, so that her fruit depart from her, and yet no mischief follow: he shall be surely punished... And if any mischief follow, then thou shalt give life for life."'),
('Exodus', 21, 'teens', 5, 'What distinction did the law make between murder and accidental killing?', 'If someone killed accidentally (God delivered the victim into his hand), God provided a place of refuge; but premeditated murder deserved death, even if the killer fled to God''s altar', 'No distinction was made', 'Accidental killing was punished equally', 'Murder was punished with a fine only', 'a', 'Exodus 21:12-14 — "He that smiteth a man, so that he die, shall be surely put to death. And if a man lie not in wait, but God deliver him into his hand; then I will appoint thee a place whither he shall flee."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 21, 'adults', 1, 'How does the "Book of the Covenant" (chapters 21-23) relate to the Decalogue?', 'The Book of the Covenant provides case law (casuistic law) that applies the general principles of the Ten Commandments to specific situations — it is the practical outworking of the Decalogue in daily life', 'It replaces the Ten Commandments', 'It contradicts the Decalogue', 'It is unrelated to the Decalogue', 'a', 'Exodus 21-23 expand the Decalogue into case law. "Thou shalt not kill" (20:13) becomes detailed laws about murder, manslaughter, assault, and negligence (21:12-36). "Thou shalt not steal" (20:15) becomes laws about property, restitution, and economic justice.'),
('Exodus', 21, 'adults', 2, 'How does the "eye for eye" (lex talionis) function in its original context?', 'It limits vengeance — the punishment must not exceed the crime; far from promoting violence, it prevents blood feuds by establishing proportional justice, replacing unlimited retaliation with measured response', 'It promotes unlimited revenge', 'It is a call to literal mutilation', 'It was never actually applied', 'a', 'Exodus 21:24 — "Eye for eye, tooth for tooth." The lex talionis was a legal reform limiting retribution. In practice, monetary compensation often substituted for literal application (cf. 21:30). Jesus'' teaching in Matthew 5:38-39 transcends it with grace, but the original intent was justice, not cruelty.'),
('Exodus', 21, 'adults', 3, 'How does the voluntary servitude law (21:5-6) typologically point to Christ?', 'The servant who chooses permanent bondage out of love for his master pictures Christ, who "took upon him the form of a servant" (Philippians 2:7) voluntarily — the pierced ear echoes the piercing at the cross, and love motivates the choice', 'There is no connection', 'Christ was forced into service', 'The servant was coerced', 'a', 'Exodus 21:5-6 — "I love my master... I will not go out free" → ear pierced at the door. Psalm 40:6 (Hebrews 10:5-7): "Mine ears hast thou opened" (or "digged/pierced"). Christ''s servitude is voluntary, motivated by love — the perfect fulfilment of the willing servant.'),
('Exodus', 21, 'adults', 4, 'What does the ox-goring law establish about negligence and liability?', 'It establishes the legal principle of strict liability for known dangers — an owner who knows an animal is dangerous and fails to restrain it bears responsibility for the consequences; this is the foundation of modern negligence law', 'Only intentional harm was punished', 'Animals could not cause legal liability', 'Owners were never responsible', 'a', 'Exodus 21:29,36 — The distinction between a first-time goring (ox killed, owner guiltless) and a habitual gorer (owner warned, both ox and owner liable) establishes the legal concept of scienter — prior knowledge of danger creates responsibility.'),
('Exodus', 21, 'adults', 5, 'How do the servant laws of Exodus 21 compare to contemporary Ancient Near Eastern laws?', 'They are significantly more humane than surrounding codes — the Code of Hammurabi prescribed death for harbouring runaway slaves and had no mandatory release; Israel''s laws protected servants'' bodily integrity and guaranteed freedom after six years', 'They were identical to Hammurabi''s Code', 'They were harsher than surrounding laws', 'No comparison is possible', 'a', 'Exodus 21:2,26-27 — Israel''s servant laws were revolutionary: six-year release, freedom for bodily injury, prohibition of return to slavery (Deuteronomy 23:15-16). Compare Hammurabi''s Code §§15-20 which prescribed death for anyone helping a slave escape.'),
('Exodus', 21, 'adults', 6, 'What does the kidnapping prohibition (21:16) reveal about the biblical view of human dignity?', 'Manstealing (kidnapping for sale or forced labour) is a capital offence — every human being bears God''s image and cannot be treated as property to be bought and sold; this law fundamentally undermines any justification for chattel slavery', 'Kidnapping was a minor offence', 'Only Israelites were protected', 'The law was rarely enforced', 'a', 'Exodus 21:16 — "He that stealeth a man, and selleth him... shall surely be put to death." Paul cites "menstealers" (andrapodistai) in 1 Timothy 1:10 among those who violate sound doctrine. This law was foundational for abolitionist arguments against the Atlantic slave trade.'),
('Exodus', 21, 'adults', 7, 'How does the law about the open pit (21:33-34) establish principles of social responsibility?', 'If someone digs a pit and does not cover it, they are liable for any animal that falls in — establishing that we are responsible not only for our direct actions but also for foreseeable dangers our negligence creates', 'Pit-digging was prohibited', 'Only the animal owner was responsible', 'No liability existed for negligence', 'a', 'Exodus 21:33-34 — "If a man shall open a pit, or if a man shall dig a pit, and not cover it, and an ox or an ass fall therein; The owner of the pit shall make it good." This establishes positive duty of care — responsibility extends to preventing foreseeable harm, not merely avoiding direct violence.'),
('Exodus', 21, 'adults', 8, 'What does the phrase "God deliver him into his hand" (21:13) suggest about divine providence in accidental death?', 'It acknowledges God''s sovereignty even in seemingly random events — accidental death is not outside God''s providential governance; this theology of providence does not blame God for evil but recognises His mysterious rule over all circumstances', 'It means God causes accidents deliberately', 'It removes all human responsibility', 'It is a figure of speech with no theology', 'a', 'Exodus 21:13 — "If a man lie not in wait, but God deliver him into his hand." This phrase reflects a robust theology of providence: even events without human intention fall within God''s sovereign ordering. The practical result is that the manslayer receives refuge rather than vengeance.');

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 22 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 22, 'kids', 1, 'If someone stole an ox or sheep, what did they have to pay back?', 'Five oxen for one ox and four sheep for one sheep — much more than they took', 'Only one animal back', 'Nothing at all', 'Half an animal', 'a', 'Exodus 22:1 — "If a man shall steal an ox, or a sheep, and kill it, or sell it; he shall restore five oxen for an ox, and four sheep for a sheep."'),
('Exodus', 22, 'kids', 2, 'What special people does God say we must not mistreat?', 'Strangers (foreigners), widows, and fatherless children — because the Israelites were strangers in Egypt', 'Only the wealthy and powerful', 'Only the king and his family', 'Only the priests', 'a', 'Exodus 22:21-22 — "Thou shalt neither vex a stranger, nor oppress him: for ye were strangers in the land of Egypt. Ye shall not afflict any widow, or fatherless child."'),
('Exodus', 22, 'kids', 3, 'What did God say about lending money to poor people?', 'Do not charge them interest — do not be like a money-lender who takes advantage of the poor', 'Charge them double interest', 'Do not lend to them at all', 'Make them work for it', 'a', 'Exodus 22:25 — "If thou lend money to any of my people that is poor by thee, thou shalt not be to him as an usurer, neither shalt thou lay upon him usury."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 22, 'teens', 1, 'What restitution principle does this chapter establish for theft?', 'Multiple restitution: five-fold for an ox, four-fold for a sheep; double for stolen goods found alive; and if the thief cannot pay, he must be sold to make restitution', 'Simply return what was stolen', 'Pay a small fine', 'No punishment at all', 'a', 'Exodus 22:1,3-4 — The graduated restitution (5x ox, 4x sheep, 2x live animals found) reflects the economic value of the item and the severity of the theft. An ox was a work animal (more valuable), hence higher restitution.'),
('Exodus', 22, 'teens', 2, 'What does God say about a person who practices sorcery?', '"Thou shalt not suffer a witch to live" — sorcery was a capital offence in Israel', 'Sorcery was permitted', 'Witches were fined', 'They were sent to other nations', 'a', 'Exodus 22:18 — "Thou shalt not suffer a witch to live." The Hebrew mechashephah refers to practitioners of occult arts — those who sought power from sources other than Yahweh. This prohibition protected Israel''s exclusive devotion to God.'),
('Exodus', 22, 'teens', 3, 'What warning does God give about mistreating widows and orphans?', '"If thou afflict them in any wise, and they cry at all unto me, I will surely hear their cry; And my wrath shall wax hot, and I will kill you with the sword"', 'There is no specific warning', 'They should take care of themselves', 'Only the rich need to help them', 'a', 'Exodus 22:23-24 — "If thou afflict them in any wise, and they cry at all unto me, I will surely hear their cry; And my wrath shall wax hot, and I will kill you with the sword; and your wives shall be widows, and your children fatherless."'),
('Exodus', 22, 'teens', 4, 'What rule protected borrowers who gave their cloak as security for a loan?', 'The cloak had to be returned by sunset because it was the person''s only covering for sleeping — "wherein shall he sleep?"', 'The lender could keep it permanently', 'The cloak was destroyed', 'A new cloak was provided', 'a', 'Exodus 22:26-27 — "If thou at all take thy neighbour''s raiment to pledge, thou shalt deliver it unto him by that the sun goeth down: For that is his covering only... wherein shall he sleep?"'),
('Exodus', 22, 'teens', 5, 'What did God command about giving the firstfruits?', '"Thou shalt not delay to offer the first of thy ripe fruits, and of thy liquors: the firstborn of thy sons shalt thou give unto me"', 'Give the last of the harvest', 'Give only if there was surplus', 'Give once every ten years', 'a', 'Exodus 22:29 — "Thou shalt not delay to offer the first of thy ripe fruits, and of thy liquors: the firstborn of thy sons shalt thou give unto me."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 22, 'adults', 1, 'How does the restitution principle in Exodus 22 differ from modern criminal justice?', 'It prioritises restoration to the victim over punishment of the offender — the focus is making the victim whole through multiple restitution rather than incarceration; the offender repays society through the victim, not through imprisonment', 'It focuses on imprisonment', 'It ignores victims entirely', 'It is identical to modern systems', 'a', 'Exodus 22:1-15 — The restitution model is restorative: the thief repays the victim (not the state) with multiplied compensation. This victim-centred justice contrasts with modern systems where offenders serve time but victims receive little direct compensation.'),
('Exodus', 22, 'adults', 2, 'What does the prohibition against charging interest to the poor reveal about biblical economics?', 'It challenges the commodification of human need — lending to the poor is an act of compassion, not a business opportunity; charging interest to the vulnerable exploits their desperation, violating covenant community ethics', 'Interest was always prohibited', 'Only high interest was forbidden', 'The law was purely symbolic', 'a', 'Exodus 22:25 — "Thou shalt not be to him as an usurer (nosheh), neither shalt thou lay upon him usury (neshekh — literally ''bite'')." The metaphor of interest as a "bite" captures its predatory nature. This prohibition was revolutionary in the ancient world.'),
('Exodus', 22, 'adults', 3, 'How does God''s self-identification as "gracious" (channun) in 22:27 connect to the protection of the poor?', 'God identifies His own character as the basis for social legislation — He is gracious to the vulnerable, therefore His people must be; the law reflects the character of the Lawgiver, making social justice a theological imperative, not merely ethical preference', 'God''s character is unrelated to law', 'Grace only applies to forgiveness', 'Only priests need to be gracious', 'a', 'Exodus 22:27 — "For I am gracious." God grounds the cloak-return law in His own character — He is channun (gracious, compassionate). This establishes the principle that ethics flow from theology: we treat others as God treats us.'),
('Exodus', 22, 'adults', 4, 'What does the self-defence provision (22:2-3) about a thief breaking in at night teach?', 'Killing a night-time intruder is not murder (no bloodguilt), but killing a daytime thief is (bloodguilt applies) — the distinction rests on whether the homeowner could reasonably perceive a lethal threat; at night, uncertainty justifies lethal force', 'All killing of thieves was permitted', 'No self-defence was allowed', 'The time of day was irrelevant', 'a', 'Exodus 22:2-3 — "If a thief be found breaking up, and be smitten that he die, there shall no blood be shed for him. If the sun be risen upon him, there shall be blood shed for him." This nuanced law distinguishes between justified self-defence (night) and excessive force (day).'),
('Exodus', 22, 'adults', 5, 'How does "thou shalt not revile the gods (elohim)" in 22:28 connect to civil authority?', 'The Hebrew elohim here likely means "judges" or "rulers" (as in 21:6) — the prohibition against cursing leadership reflects the biblical principle that governing authorities derive their legitimacy from God and must be respected, even when criticized', 'It refers only to pagan gods', 'It prohibits all criticism of leaders', 'It is a mistranslation', 'a', 'Exodus 22:28 — "Thou shalt not revile the gods (elohim), nor curse the ruler of thy people." Paul quotes this in Acts 23:5 when he apologises for unknowingly insulting the high priest, interpreting elohim as human rulers.'),
('Exodus', 22, 'adults', 6, 'What does the seduction law (22:16-17) reveal about the value placed on women?', 'The seducer must marry the woman and pay the bride price — if the father refuses, the seducer still pays the full bride price; this protects the woman economically, ensuring she is not left without support or social standing after being dishonoured', 'Women had no economic protection', 'The woman was punished', 'Only the father was compensated', 'a', 'Exodus 22:16-17 — The law addresses the practical consequence: a seduced virgin''s marriage prospects were damaged. The required bride-price (mohar) whether or not marriage occurred ensured the woman was not left economically vulnerable by male irresponsibility.'),
('Exodus', 22, 'adults', 7, 'How does "ye were strangers in the land of Egypt" function as an ethical argument?', 'It grounds ethics in shared experience — because Israel experienced the vulnerability of being aliens in Egypt, they must empathise with strangers; the argument from memory creates moral obligation: those who have been delivered from oppression must not become oppressors', 'It was a historical footnote', 'It applied only to Egyptians', 'It was optional guidance', 'a', 'Exodus 22:21 — "For ye were strangers in the land of Egypt." This experiential argument appears repeatedly (23:9, Leviticus 19:34, Deuteronomy 10:19). Israel''s memory of suffering becomes the basis for compassion — the golden rule applied nationally.'),
('Exodus', 22, 'adults', 8, 'What does the prohibition against boiling a kid in its mother''s milk (22:19) likely address?', 'It probably prohibits a Canaanite fertility ritual — the Ugaritic texts describe such practices; separating the life-giving (milk) from the life-taking (slaughter) reflects a broader biblical principle of not mixing categories that God has distinguished', 'It is a dietary preference', 'It prevents food poisoning', 'It has no religious context', 'a', 'Exodus 22:19 (some versions 23:19) — "Thou shalt not seethe a kid in his mother''s milk." This prohibition appears three times (also 34:26, Deuteronomy 14:21). The most likely explanation is anti-Canaanite polemic: Israel must not adopt pagan fertility practices.');

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 23 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 23, 'kids', 1, 'What did God say about telling lies in court?', '"Thou shalt not raise a false report" and "keep thee far from a false matter" — always tell the truth', '"Sometimes lying is okay"', '"Only lie to strangers"', '"Lie if it helps you"', 'a', 'Exodus 23:1,7 — "Thou shalt not raise a false report: put not thine hand with the wicked to be an unrighteous witness... Keep thee far from a false matter."'),
('Exodus', 23, 'kids', 2, 'How many special feasts did God command the Israelites to celebrate each year?', 'Three feasts — the Feast of Unleavened Bread, the Feast of Harvest, and the Feast of Ingathering', 'One feast', 'Seven feasts', 'No feasts at all', 'a', 'Exodus 23:14 — "Three times thou shalt keep a feast unto me in the year."'),
('Exodus', 23, 'kids', 3, 'What did God promise to send ahead of the Israelites to prepare the way?', 'An Angel to keep them in the way and bring them to the Promised Land', 'A mighty army', 'A golden chariot', 'A flying bird', 'a', 'Exodus 23:20 — "Behold, I send an Angel before thee, to keep thee in the way, and to bring thee into the place which I have prepared."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 23, 'teens', 1, 'What surprising command does God give about your enemy''s lost animal?', '"If thou meet thine enemy''s ox or his ass going astray, thou shalt surely bring it back to him again" — help even your enemies', 'Leave it to wander', 'Keep it for yourself', 'Drive it further away', 'a', 'Exodus 23:4 — "If thou meet thine enemy''s ox or his ass going astray, thou shalt surely bring it back to him again."'),
('Exodus', 23, 'teens', 2, 'What rest did God command for the land every seventh year?', 'Let the land rest — do not plant or harvest so that the poor and wild animals may eat what grows naturally', 'Plant double crops', 'Build more houses on the land', 'Sell the land', 'a', 'Exodus 23:10-11 — "And six years thou shalt sow thy land, and shalt gather in the fruits thereof: But the seventh year thou shalt let it rest and lie still; that the poor of thy people may eat."'),
('Exodus', 23, 'teens', 3, 'What three feasts are listed and when do they occur?', 'Unleavened Bread (Abib/spring, marking the exodus), Harvest/Firstfruits (early summer), and Ingathering/Tabernacles (autumn, end of harvest)', 'Passover, Purim, and Hanukkah', 'Pentecost, Christmas, and Easter', 'New Year, Sabbath, and Jubilee', 'a', 'Exodus 23:15-16 — "The feast of unleavened bread... in the time appointed of the month Abib... the feast of harvest, the firstfruits of thy labours... the feast of ingathering, which is in the end of the year."'),
('Exodus', 23, 'teens', 4, 'How would God drive out the nations from the Promised Land?', 'Little by little, not all at once — lest the land become desolate and wild beasts multiply', 'All at once with a great earthquake', 'By sending a flood', 'By making them disappear instantly', 'a', 'Exodus 23:29-30 — "I will not drive them out from before thee in one year; lest the land become desolate, and the beast of the field multiply against thee. By little and little I will drive them out from before thee."'),
('Exodus', 23, 'teens', 5, 'What warning did God give about the gods of the other nations?', '"Thou shalt not bow down to their gods, nor serve them, nor do after their works: but thou shalt utterly overthrow them, and quite break down their images"', '"Study their gods to understand them"', '"Worship their gods alongside the LORD"', '"Trade idols with them"', 'a', 'Exodus 23:24 — "Thou shalt not bow down to their gods, nor serve them, nor do after their works: but thou shalt utterly overthrow them, and quite break down their images."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 23, 'adults', 1, 'How does the command to help your enemy''s animal (23:4-5) anticipate Jesus'' teaching on enemy love?', 'It extends moral obligation beyond personal feelings — you must do right even toward those who hate you; this concrete action-based ethic anticipates Matthew 5:44 ("love your enemies") by grounding love not in emotion but in practical duty', 'It contradicts Jesus'' teaching', 'It applies only to animals', 'It was never practiced', 'a', 'Exodus 23:4-5 — These laws mandate concrete help for enemies, making hostility irrelevant to moral duty. Jesus'' command to love enemies (Matthew 5:44) does not introduce a new ethic but intensifies what was already present in the Torah.'),
('Exodus', 23, 'adults', 2, 'What does the sabbatical year provision (23:10-11) reveal about the theology of land ownership?', 'The land ultimately belongs to God — Israel holds it in trust; the seventh-year rest acknowledges divine ownership, provides for the poor, and teaches Israel that productivity depends on God''s blessing, not human exploitation of the soil', 'The land belonged to farmers absolutely', 'The sabbatical year was optional', 'Only rich farmers had to observe it', 'a', 'Exodus 23:10-11 — The sabbatical year asserts God''s ownership (Leviticus 25:23: "The land is mine; for ye are strangers and sojourners with me"). It also serves ecological, social (feeding the poor), and theological (trust in God''s provision) purposes.'),
('Exodus', 23, 'adults', 3, 'What does the Angel in 23:20-23 represent, and what is the significance of "my name is in him"?', 'The Angel is likely a theophanic manifestation of God Himself — "my name is in him" means God''s essential nature and authority reside in this Angel, making disobedience to the Angel equal to disobedience to God; many identify this as the pre-incarnate Christ', 'It was an ordinary angel', 'It was Moses in disguise', 'It was a metaphor for the law', 'a', 'Exodus 23:20-21 — "Behold, I send an Angel before thee... Beware of him, and obey his voice, provoke him not; for he will not pardon your transgressions: for my name is in him." The authority to forgive or not forgive transgressions is divine prerogative, suggesting this Angel is the Angel of the LORD — a Christophany.'),
('Exodus', 23, 'adults', 4, 'Why does God command the gradual dispossession of the Canaanites rather than immediate conquest?', 'Practical wisdom — depopulated land would revert to wilderness with dangerous animals; Israel needed to grow numerically to fill the land; God''s patience also gave the inhabitants time to respond (as Rahab later did)', 'God lacked the power for immediate conquest', 'The Canaanites were innocent', 'Gradual conquest was Moses'' idea', 'a', 'Exodus 23:29-30 — "By little and little I will drive them out." This reveals God''s pragmatic wisdom: conquest must match Israel''s capacity to settle. It also demonstrates that God''s timetable is often gradual, requiring sustained faithfulness.'),
('Exodus', 23, 'adults', 5, 'How do the three pilgrimage festivals map onto Israel''s agricultural and redemptive calendar?', 'Unleavened Bread (spring: barley harvest + exodus remembrance), Harvest/Weeks (summer: wheat harvest + Sinai giving of law), Ingathering/Tabernacles (autumn: fruit harvest + wilderness journey) — each combines agricultural thanksgiving with theological memory', 'They are purely agricultural', 'They are purely theological', 'They have no consistent pattern', 'a', 'Exodus 23:14-17 — The three festivals unite creation and redemption: each celebrates God''s provision in nature (harvest) while commemorating God''s acts in history (exodus, Sinai, wilderness). This integration of nature and history is distinctively Israelite.'),
('Exodus', 23, 'adults', 6, 'What does the prohibition against following a multitude to do evil (23:2) teach about moral courage?', 'It prohibits mob mentality and peer pressure in judicial proceedings — truth is not determined by majority opinion; a single righteous witness must not bend his testimony to align with a corrupt majority', 'It promotes democratic decision-making', 'It was only about court proceedings', 'Majority opinion is always right', 'a', 'Exodus 23:2 — "Thou shalt not follow a multitude to do evil; neither shalt thou speak in a cause to decline after many to wrest judgment." This is a fundamental principle of moral independence: right is not determined by consensus but by God''s standard.'),
('Exodus', 23, 'adults', 7, 'What does "thou shalt not wrest the judgment of thy poor in his cause" (23:6) reveal about judicial bias?', 'It prohibits discrimination against the poor in court — while 23:3 warns against favouring the poor out of pity, 23:6 warns against disadvantaging them out of contempt; justice must be blind to both wealth and poverty', 'Courts should always favour the poor', 'The wealthy deserve better treatment', 'The poor have no legal rights', 'a', 'Exodus 23:3,6 — The twin prohibitions (don''t favour the poor in 23:3, don''t disadvantage the poor in 23:6) establish strict judicial impartiality. Justice is neither pro-rich nor pro-poor but pro-truth, regardless of the parties'' social status.'),
('Exodus', 23, 'adults', 8, 'How does God''s promise to "send my fear before thee" and "hornets" (23:27-28) demonstrate divine warfare?', 'God fights for Israel using psychological weapons (terror/confusion) and natural agents (hornets) — victory comes not primarily through military prowess but through God''s supernatural intervention, establishing that the conquest is God''s war, not Israel''s', 'Israel conquered solely by military might', 'Hornets were metaphorical for diseases', 'God played no role in the conquest', 'a', 'Exodus 23:27-28 — "I will send my fear before thee, and will destroy all the people to whom thou shalt come... And I will send hornets before thee." Whether literal or metaphorical, these weapons emphasise that the conquest is divinely accomplished, not humanly achieved.');

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 24 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 24, 'kids', 1, 'What did the people say when Moses read God''s laws to them?', '"All the words which the LORD hath said will we do" — they promised to obey everything', '"We will think about it"', '"Only some of the laws"', '"We do not agree"', 'a', 'Exodus 24:3 — "And Moses came and told the people all the words of the LORD, and all the judgments: and all the people answered with one voice, and said, All the words which the LORD hath said will we do."'),
('Exodus', 24, 'kids', 2, 'What did the ground under God''s feet look like when the elders saw God?', 'Like a paved work of sapphire stone, as clear as the sky — beautiful blue', 'Like green grass', 'Like red fire', 'Like white snow', 'a', 'Exodus 24:10 — "And they saw the God of Israel: and there was under his feet as it were a paved work of a sapphire stone, and as it were the body of heaven in his clearness."'),
('Exodus', 24, 'kids', 3, 'How many days was Moses on the mountain with God?', 'Forty days and forty nights', 'Seven days', 'Three days', 'One hundred days', 'a', 'Exodus 24:18 — "And Moses went into the midst of the cloud, and gat him up into the mount: and Moses was in the mount forty days and forty nights."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 24, 'teens', 1, 'What did Moses sprinkle on the people to seal the covenant?', 'Blood from the burnt offerings — calling it "the blood of the covenant which the LORD hath made with you"', 'Water from the river', 'Oil from the tabernacle', 'Wine from the altar', 'a', 'Exodus 24:8 — "And Moses took the blood, and sprinkled it on the people, and said, Behold the blood of the covenant, which the LORD hath made with you concerning all these words."'),
('Exodus', 24, 'teens', 2, 'Who went up the mountain with Moses?', 'Aaron, Nadab, Abihu, and seventy of the elders of Israel — they saw God and ate and drank in His presence', 'Only Moses went alone', 'The entire nation went up', 'Only Aaron went with Moses', 'a', 'Exodus 24:9-11 — "Then went up Moses, and Aaron, Nadab, and Abihu, and seventy of the elders of Israel: And they saw the God of Israel... also they saw God, and did eat and drink."'),
('Exodus', 24, 'teens', 3, 'What did God promise to give Moses on the mountain?', 'Tables of stone with the law and commandments written by God''s own hand', 'A golden crown', 'A royal robe', 'A book of prophecies', 'a', 'Exodus 24:12 — "And the LORD said unto Moses, Come up to me into the mount, and be there: and I will give thee tables of stone, and a law, and commandments which I have written."'),
('Exodus', 24, 'teens', 4, 'What did the glory of the LORD look like to the Israelites from below?', 'Like devouring fire on the top of the mount', 'Like a gentle light', 'Like a rainbow', 'Like a waterfall', 'a', 'Exodus 24:17 — "And the sight of the glory of the LORD was like devouring fire on the top of the mount in the eyes of the children of Israel."'),
('Exodus', 24, 'teens', 5, 'Who did Moses leave in charge while he went up the mountain?', 'Aaron and Hur — "if any man have any matters to do, let him come unto them"', 'Joshua alone', 'The seventy elders', 'Miriam', 'a', 'Exodus 24:14 — "And he said unto the elders, Tarry ye here for us, until we come again unto you: and, behold, Aaron and Hur are with you: if any man have any matters to do, let him come unto them."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 24, 'adults', 1, 'How does the blood of the covenant (24:8) connect to Jesus'' words at the Last Supper?', 'Jesus explicitly echoes Exodus 24:8 when He says "This is my blood of the new testament" (Matthew 26:28) — the old covenant was ratified with animal blood; the new covenant is ratified with Christ''s own blood, fulfilling and surpassing the Sinai covenant', 'Jesus never referenced this passage', 'The connection is modern invention', 'The blood was unrelated to covenant', 'a', 'Exodus 24:8, Matthew 26:28 — "Behold the blood of the covenant" becomes "This is my blood of the new testament, which is shed for many for the remission of sins." Hebrews 9:18-20 explicitly connects the two, stating the first covenant was dedicated with blood.'),
('Exodus', 24, 'adults', 2, 'What is the theological significance of the elders eating and drinking in God''s presence?', 'The covenant meal represents intimate fellowship with God — seeing God and sharing food without being destroyed demonstrates that covenant relationship enables sinful humans to dwell with a holy God; this meal anticipates the eschatological banquet (Isaiah 25:6, Revelation 19:9)', 'It was an ordinary meal', 'They were not actually in God''s presence', 'Eating was prohibited in God''s presence', 'a', 'Exodus 24:11 — "Upon the nobles of the children of Israel he laid not his hand: also they saw God, and did eat and drink." The phrase "laid not his hand" implies they deserved death but received mercy — covenant grace enables what justice would prohibit.'),
('Exodus', 24, 'adults', 3, 'How does the sapphire pavement (24:10) connect to other biblical theophanies?', 'Ezekiel 1:26 describes the throne of God above a "firmament... as the colour of the terrible crystal" with a sapphire throne — the sapphire imagery links the Sinai vision to Ezekiel''s vision and Revelation''s descriptions, forming a consistent imagery of the divine throne', 'No other vision mentions sapphire', 'Sapphire was a common building material', 'The description was figurative only', 'a', 'Exodus 24:10, Ezekiel 1:26 — Both describe a sapphire-like surface associated with God''s presence. Revelation 4:6 adds the "sea of glass, like unto crystal" before the throne. This recurring imagery creates a consistent visual theology of heaven''s throne room.'),
('Exodus', 24, 'adults', 4, 'What does the bipartite blood ritual (half on the altar, half on the people) signify?', 'Blood on the altar represents God''s side of the covenant; blood on the people represents their side — both parties are bound by the same blood, creating a shared life-bond; violation of the covenant invokes the curse symbolised by the slaughtered animals', 'The blood was divided randomly', 'Only the altar blood mattered', 'Only the people''s blood mattered', 'a', 'Exodus 24:6-8 — Moses divides the blood: half sprinkled on the altar (God''s representative) and half on the people. This binds both parties in a blood covenant — the most solemn form of ancient agreement, implying "may this happen to me if I break this covenant."'),
('Exodus', 24, 'adults', 5, 'Why does Moses write "all the words of the LORD" (24:4) before the covenant ceremony?', 'Written documentation is essential for covenant validity — oral agreement is insufficient for a binding covenant; the written record provides objective accountability and ensures the terms cannot be altered or forgotten; this principle underlies the doctrine of Scripture', 'Writing was unnecessary', 'The covenant was purely oral', 'Moses wrote from memory later', 'a', 'Exodus 24:4 — "And Moses wrote all the words of the LORD." Written covenant documents are paralleled in ancient treaty practice. This writing establishes Scripture as the covenant document — the authoritative record of God''s terms to which both parties are accountable.'),
('Exodus', 24, 'adults', 6, 'How does Joshua''s presence on the mountain (24:13) foreshadow his future role?', 'Joshua accompanied Moses partway up the mountain, positioning him as Moses'' closest associate and eventual successor — his proximity to the divine encounter on Sinai prepared him for leadership when Moses could not enter the Promised Land', 'Joshua went all the way to the top', 'Joshua stayed at the camp', 'Joshua was absent from this event', 'a', 'Exodus 24:13 — "And Moses rose up, and his minister Joshua: and Moses went up into the mount of God." Joshua''s role as Moses'' "minister" (mesharet — attendant/servant) throughout the Pentateuch prepares for his commissioning in Deuteronomy 31 and leadership in the book bearing his name.'),
('Exodus', 24, 'adults', 7, 'What is the function of the forty-day period on the mountain?', 'The forty days provide time for God to reveal the tabernacle blueprints in detail — this extended communion transforms Moses (34:29-30) and establishes forty as a biblical number of testing, preparation, and divine encounter (Jesus'' forty days, Elijah''s journey)', 'Forty days was arbitrary', 'Moses chose the duration', 'It was actually less than forty days', 'a', 'Exodus 24:18 — Forty days on the mountain establishes a pattern: Israel''s forty years in the wilderness, Elijah''s forty-day journey to Horeb (1 Kings 19:8), Jesus'' forty days of fasting (Matthew 4:2). The number signifies a complete period of divine preparation.'),
('Exodus', 24, 'adults', 8, 'How does the statement "they saw the God of Israel" (24:10) relate to the broader biblical teaching that no one can see God and live?', 'The tension is deliberate — they saw a manifestation of God''s glory (the sapphire pavement, the consuming fire) without seeing the divine essence; "they saw God" describes a genuine encounter short of the unmediated vision of God''s full glory that would be fatal (33:20)', 'They saw God fully without limitation', 'The text is contradicting itself', 'They did not actually see anything', 'a', 'Exodus 24:10-11, 33:20 — "They saw God, and did eat and drink" (24:11), yet "There shall no man see me, and live" (33:20). The resolution: they experienced a real theophany — an accommodated revelation of God''s presence — without seeing the unbearable fullness of His divine essence.');

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 25 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 25, 'kids', 1, 'What did God tell Moses to build so He could dwell among His people?', 'A sanctuary (tabernacle) — a special tent where God''s presence would live', 'A stone castle', 'A tall tower', 'A golden palace', 'a', 'Exodus 25:8 — "And let them make me a sanctuary; that I may dwell among them."'),
('Exodus', 25, 'kids', 2, 'What was the most special piece of furniture inside the tabernacle?', 'The Ark of the Covenant — a gold-covered box with two golden angels (cherubim) on top', 'A large table', 'A big bed', 'A cooking oven', 'a', 'Exodus 25:10-11 — "And they shall make an ark of shittim wood... And thou shalt overlay it with pure gold."'),
('Exodus', 25, 'kids', 3, 'What beautiful lampstand was made of pure gold?', 'A candlestick (menorah) with seven branches — six branches coming from the sides and one in the middle', 'A lamp with one light', 'A candle in a jar', 'A torch on a stick', 'a', 'Exodus 25:31-32 — "And thou shalt make a candlestick of pure gold... six branches shall come out of the sides of it."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 25, 'teens', 1, 'What kind of offerings did God request for building the tabernacle?', 'Willing offerings from the heart — gold, silver, brass, blue/purple/scarlet fabric, fine linen, goat hair, ram skins, badger skins, wood, oil, spices, and precious stones', 'Forced taxes from every family', 'Only gold and silver', 'Only what was left over', 'a', 'Exodus 25:2-7 — "Speak unto the children of Israel, that they bring me an offering: of every man that giveth it willingly with his heart ye shall take my offering."'),
('Exodus', 25, 'teens', 2, 'What was placed inside the Ark of the Covenant?', 'The testimony (the two stone tablets of the law) — later, a pot of manna and Aaron''s rod that budded were also placed inside or before it', 'Gold and silver coins', 'A scroll of names', 'Food offerings', 'a', 'Exodus 25:16 — "And thou shalt put into the ark the testimony which I shall give thee." Hebrews 9:4 adds the golden pot of manna and Aaron''s rod.'),
('Exodus', 25, 'teens', 3, 'What was on top of the Ark?', 'The mercy seat — a pure gold cover with two cherubim facing each other with wings spread over it; God said He would meet Moses there', 'A golden crown', 'A burning flame', 'A precious stone', 'a', 'Exodus 25:17-22 — "And thou shalt make a mercy seat of pure gold... And thou shalt make two cherubims of gold... And there I will meet with thee, and I will commune with thee from above the mercy seat."'),
('Exodus', 25, 'teens', 4, 'What was the Table of Shewbread for?', 'Twelve loaves of bread were placed on it before the LORD — representing the twelve tribes of Israel in God''s presence', 'Displaying gold objects', 'Holding the scrolls', 'Serving meals to priests', 'a', 'Exodus 25:30 — "And thou shalt set upon the table shewbread before me alway." Leviticus 24:5-6 specifies twelve cakes, changed weekly.'),
('Exodus', 25, 'teens', 5, 'What instruction did God repeatedly give Moses about building?', '"Look that thou make them after their pattern, which was shewed thee in the mount" — build everything exactly as God showed', 'Use your own creativity', 'Copy Egyptian temples', 'Follow the people''s suggestions', 'a', 'Exodus 25:40 — "And look that thou make them after their pattern, which was shewed thee in the mount."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 25, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological significance of "let them make me a sanctuary; that I may dwell among them"?', 'It reveals that God''s ultimate purpose in redemption is dwelling with His people — the exodus was not merely rescue from slavery but restoration of communion; the tabernacle makes God''s presence tangible and accessible, fulfilling and foreshadowing the Incarnation (John 1:14 — "the Word was made flesh and dwelt/tabernacled among us")', 'The tabernacle was merely a religious building', 'God already dwelt among them', 'The dwelling was metaphorical only', 'a', 'Exodus 25:8 — "That I may dwell among them." The Hebrew shakan ("to dwell/tabernacle") gives us the Shekinah. John 1:14 uses skenoo ("to tabernacle") — Jesus is the ultimate fulfilment of God dwelling among humanity.'),
('Exodus', 25, 'adults', 2, 'How does the Ark of the Covenant function theologically?', 'It serves as God''s throne on earth — the mercy seat between the cherubim is where God''s glory dwells; it contains the law (covenant terms), is covered by mercy (the mercy seat/kapporet — place of atonement), and is the meeting point between God and man', 'It is merely a storage container', 'It had no theological significance', 'It was an Egyptian practice', 'a', 'Exodus 25:22 — "I will meet with thee, and I will commune with thee from above the mercy seat." The Ark combines three realities: God''s throne (His presence), God''s covenant (the tablets), and God''s mercy (the kapporet where blood was sprinkled on Yom Kippur).'),
('Exodus', 25, 'adults', 3, 'What does the menorah (golden candlestick) symbolise?', 'Its seven lights provide the only illumination in the Holy Place — symbolising God as the source of light, spiritual illumination, and the tree of life (its almond-blossom design echoes Eden''s tree); Jesus claims to be "the light of the world" (John 8:12)', 'It was merely decorative', 'It was a common household item', 'It had no symbolic meaning', 'a', 'Exodus 25:31-40 — The menorah''s botanical design (almond blossoms, buds, flowers) suggests a tree of life motif. Its seven branches may represent completeness or creation. As the sole light source in the Holy Place, it symbolises divine illumination.'),
('Exodus', 25, 'adults', 4, 'Why does God specify "willing" offerings (25:2) and what does this teach about worship?', 'Compelled giving is not true worship — God desires offerings from a generous heart, not dutiful obligation; this principle echoes throughout Scripture (2 Corinthians 9:7 — "God loveth a cheerful giver") and distinguishes biblical worship from pagan obligation', 'All offerings were mandatory', 'Unwilling offerings were accepted', 'Only the wealthy were asked', 'a', 'Exodus 25:2 — "Of every man that giveth it willingly with his heart." The Hebrew nedivah (willing/generous) emphasises that God values the heart''s disposition over the gift''s value. This principle governs all biblical giving.'),
('Exodus', 25, 'adults', 5, 'What does the heavenly "pattern" (tavnit) shown to Moses suggest about the tabernacle?', 'The earthly tabernacle is a copy of a heavenly reality — Hebrews 8:5 states Moses was warned to "make all things according to the pattern shewed to thee in the mount," indicating a Platonic-like relationship between the heavenly archetype and earthly copy', 'The pattern was Moses'' own design', 'There was no heavenly model', 'The pattern was from Egyptian temples', 'a', 'Exodus 25:9,40, Hebrews 8:5 — The tavnit ("pattern/model") shown on the mountain implies the earthly tabernacle corresponds to a heavenly reality. This suggests that worship, priesthood, and sacrifice on earth reflect and participate in heavenly realities.'),
('Exodus', 25, 'adults', 6, 'How does the Table of Shewbread (Bread of the Presence) point to Christ?', 'The twelve loaves represent God''s perpetual provision and fellowship with His twelve tribes — Jesus calls Himself "the bread of life" (John 6:35) and shares bread at the Last Supper; the table in God''s presence foreshadows the Eucharistic table', 'It was only about physical bread', 'It has no Christological connection', 'Only priests ate the bread', 'a', 'Exodus 25:30 — Lechem panim ("bread of the face/presence") means bread set before God''s face perpetually. The ongoing provision of bread in God''s presence anticipates Christ who says "I am the bread of life" and gives Himself as spiritual nourishment.'),
('Exodus', 25, 'adults', 7, 'What is the significance of the cherubim on the mercy seat facing each other with wings spread?', 'They represent the guardian presence of heavenly beings — facing each other and looking down at the mercy seat, they witness the blood of atonement placed there annually; their posture echoes the cherubim guarding Eden (Genesis 3:24), suggesting the tabernacle restores access to God''s presence', 'They were decorative only', 'They represented Egyptian gods', 'Their position was arbitrary', 'a', 'Exodus 25:18-20 — The cherubim on the mercy seat mirror the cherubim of Genesis 3:24 who guarded the way to God''s presence. In the tabernacle, the barrier is overcome by blood on the mercy seat — atonement restores what sin destroyed.'),
('Exodus', 25, 'adults', 8, 'How does the list of tabernacle materials (25:3-7) reflect the spoiling of the Egyptians?', 'The gold, silver, precious stones, and fine fabrics were largely obtained from the Egyptians at the exodus (11:2-3, 12:35-36) — Egypt''s wealth, originally used for idol worship and slavery, is transformed into instruments for worshipping the true God', 'The materials were mined in the wilderness', 'They brought everything from Canaan', 'The materials were created miraculously', 'a', 'Exodus 25:3-7 — The building materials trace back to the "spoiling of the Egyptians" (12:35-36). Wealth extracted through slavery is redeemed for sacred use — a powerful image of God transforming the instruments of oppression into instruments of worship.');

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 26–30 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 26 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 26, 'kids', 1, 'What was the tabernacle made of?', 'Beautiful curtains of fine linen in blue, purple, and scarlet, with cherubim woven into them', 'Stone blocks', 'Mud bricks', 'Tree bark', 'a', 'Exodus 26:1 — "Moreover thou shalt make the tabernacle with ten curtains of fine twined linen, and blue, and purple, and scarlet: with cherubims of cunning work shalt thou make them."'),
('Exodus', 26, 'kids', 2, 'What special curtain divided the tabernacle into two rooms?', 'A veil (curtain) of blue, purple, and scarlet — separating the Holy Place from the Most Holy Place', 'A stone wall', 'A wooden door', 'A metal gate', 'a', 'Exodus 26:33 — "And the vail shall divide unto you between the holy place and the most holy."'),
('Exodus', 26, 'kids', 3, 'What were the boards of the tabernacle covered with?', 'Gold — the wooden boards were overlaid with gold', 'Silver paint', 'Bronze coating', 'Copper sheets', 'a', 'Exodus 26:29 — "And thou shalt overlay the boards with gold."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 26, 'teens', 1, 'What were the four layers of coverings over the tabernacle?', 'Fine linen curtains with cherubim (innermost), goat hair curtains, ram skins dyed red, and badger (or seal) skins (outermost)', 'Only one layer of gold cloth', 'Stone tiles', 'Animal furs only', 'a', 'Exodus 26:1,7,14 — Four layers: (1) linen with cherubim, (2) goats'' hair, (3) rams'' skins dyed red, (4) badgers'' skins. The beautiful interior was hidden by a rough exterior.'),
('Exodus', 26, 'teens', 2, 'How were the curtains joined together?', 'With fifty gold clasps (taches) hooking into loops of blue along the edges', 'With rope', 'With glue', 'With wooden pegs only', 'a', 'Exodus 26:6 — "And thou shalt make fifty taches of gold, and couple the curtains together with the taches: and it shall be one tabernacle."'),
('Exodus', 26, 'teens', 3, 'What was behind the veil in the Most Holy Place?', 'The Ark of the Covenant with the mercy seat — the place of God''s presence', 'A golden throne', 'A pool of water', 'An empty room', 'a', 'Exodus 26:33-34 — "And thou shalt hang up the vail... and thou shalt bring in thither within the vail the ark of the testimony: and the vail shall divide unto you between the holy place and the most holy."'),
('Exodus', 26, 'teens', 4, 'What stood in sockets to hold the tabernacle boards upright?', 'Silver sockets — two sockets under each board, made from the redemption money of the census', 'Gold pedestals', 'Wooden stakes', 'Bronze pillars', 'a', 'Exodus 26:19 — "And thou shalt make forty sockets of silver under the twenty boards."'),
('Exodus', 26, 'teens', 5, 'What was the purpose of the five bars running through rings on the boards?', 'To hold the boards together and give the tabernacle structural strength — the middle bar ran through the entire length', 'To hang decorations', 'To carry the tabernacle', 'To divide the rooms', 'a', 'Exodus 26:26-28 — "And thou shalt make bars of shittim wood; five for the boards of the one side of the tabernacle... And the middle bar in the midst of the boards shall reach from end to end."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 26, 'adults', 1, 'How does the veil separating the Holy Place from the Most Holy Place connect to Christ''s death?', 'Matthew 27:51 records that the temple veil was torn from top to bottom when Jesus died — signifying that Christ''s death removed the barrier between God and humanity, opening direct access to God''s presence for all believers (Hebrews 10:19-20)', 'The veil has no connection to Christ', 'The veil was repaired after Christ', 'The tearing was coincidental', 'a', 'Exodus 26:31-33, Matthew 27:51, Hebrews 10:19-20 — "Having therefore, brethren, boldness to enter into the holiest by the blood of Jesus, By a new and living way, which he hath consecrated for us, through the veil, that is to say, his flesh." The torn veil represents Christ''s body broken to open access to God.'),
('Exodus', 26, 'adults', 2, 'What symbolism might the four layers of tabernacle coverings carry?', 'The beautiful inner curtains (visible only from inside) covered by progressively rougher outer layers may picture Christ — outwardly plain ("no beauty that we should desire him," Isaiah 53:2) but inwardly glorious; the rough exterior protects the sacred interior', 'The layers were purely practical', 'Each layer represented a tribe', 'The layers had no symbolic meaning', 'a', 'The four coverings: (1) Beautiful linen with cherubim — heavenly glory; (2) goats'' hair — associated with sin offerings; (3) rams'' skins dyed red — sacrifice/blood; (4) badgers'' skins — rugged protection. Many see a progressive revelation from glory (inside) through sacrifice to humble appearance (outside).'),
('Exodus', 26, 'adults', 3, 'What is the theological significance of the tabernacle being a portable structure?', 'God''s dwelling is mobile because He accompanies His people on their journey — unlike pagan temples fixed to sacred sites, Yahweh''s presence moves with Israel, demonstrating that God is not bound to any location but chooses to be with His people wherever they go', 'Portability was purely practical', 'God preferred permanent structures', 'The design was Egyptian', 'a', 'The tabernacle''s portability embodies a theology of divine accompaniment. While pagan deities were tied to cities and temples, Yahweh marches with His pilgrim people. This continues until the temple (1 Kings 8), but even then Solomon acknowledges "heaven of heavens cannot contain thee" (8:27).'),
('Exodus', 26, 'adults', 4, 'How do the silver sockets (foundation) carry redemptive symbolism?', 'Exodus 38:25-27 reveals the silver came from the half-shekel atonement money of the census — meaning the tabernacle literally stands on the foundation of redemption; every Israelite''s ransom contributed to the base upon which God''s dwelling rested', 'Silver was the cheapest available metal', 'The sockets had no special meaning', 'Gold sockets were preferred', 'a', 'Exodus 26:19, 38:25-27 — The silver sockets were made from the 100 talents of "atonement money" (30:16) — each socket from the ransom of approximately 3,000 men. The tabernacle literally rests on the foundation of redemption, just as the church is built on Christ''s atonement.'),
('Exodus', 26, 'adults', 5, 'What does the blue, purple, and scarlet colour scheme signify throughout the tabernacle?', 'Blue traditionally represents heaven/divinity, purple represents royalty, and scarlet represents sacrifice/blood — together they depict Christ as heavenly King whose royalty is expressed through sacrificial death', 'The colours were randomly chosen', 'They matched Egyptian taste', 'Only aesthetic value', 'a', 'The colour triad (tekhelet/argaman/tola''ath shani) appears throughout the tabernacle. Blue (heavenly origin), purple (kingly dignity), scarlet (sacrificial blood) — this combination points to Christ who came from heaven, reigns as King, and shed His blood for redemption.'),
('Exodus', 26, 'adults', 6, 'How does the tabernacle''s structure reflect the progressive approach to God?', 'Moving inward: outer court (all Israelites) → Holy Place (priests daily) → Most Holy Place (high priest, once yearly) — each stage increases in holiness, exclusivity, and glory, reflecting the principle that approach to God requires increasing sanctification', 'All areas were equally accessible', 'The structure was random', 'Only the High Priest entered any part', 'a', 'The tabernacle''s graduated access (court → Holy Place → Most Holy Place) teaches that God is both accessible and transcendent. Each boundary reinforces divine holiness while the entire structure makes worship possible — tension between immanence and transcendence.'),
('Exodus', 26, 'adults', 7, 'What does the cherubim motif woven into the inner curtains suggest?', 'The cherubim on the curtains echo Eden''s guardians (Genesis 3:24) — inside the tabernacle, one walks among cherubim, suggesting the tabernacle is a reconstituted Eden where God''s presence is accessible again through the sacrificial system', 'Cherubim were common decorative patterns', 'They represented Egyptian gods', 'The motif was added later', 'a', 'Exodus 26:1 — Cherubim woven into the innermost curtains create an Eden-like space. Genesis 3:24 placed cherubim as barriers to God''s presence; in the tabernacle, cherubim mark the restored space where humans may approach God through sacrifice.'),
('Exodus', 26, 'adults', 8, 'Why does God give such precise measurements and specifications for the tabernacle?', 'Precision reflects that worship must conform to God''s design, not human preference — the exact specifications teach that God determines how He is approached; this principle of regulative worship (God prescribes the form) opposes the notion that any sincere worship form is acceptable', 'The details were suggestions', 'Moses chose the measurements', 'Precise measurements were standard for all tents', 'a', 'Exodus 26 contains exacting measurements for every component. Hebrews 8:5 states Moses was warned to follow the pattern exactly. This precision establishes the regulative principle: God determines the mode and manner of acceptable worship.');

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 27 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 27, 'kids', 1, 'What was the first thing people saw when they entered the tabernacle courtyard?', 'The brazen altar (altar of burnt offering) — where animal sacrifices were offered to God', 'A golden throne', 'A large fountain', 'A garden of flowers', 'a', 'Exodus 27:1 — "And thou shalt make an altar of shittim wood, five cubits long, and five cubits broad; the altar shall be foursquare."'),
('Exodus', 27, 'kids', 2, 'What surrounded the tabernacle?', 'A courtyard with white linen curtains hung on pillars — creating a fence around the sacred area', 'A stone wall', 'A moat of water', 'A hedge of thorns', 'a', 'Exodus 27:9 — "And thou shalt make the court of the tabernacle: for the south side southward there shall be hangings for the court of fine twined linen."'),
('Exodus', 27, 'kids', 3, 'What did the people bring to keep the lamp burning?', 'Pure olive oil — beaten for the light, to keep the lamp burning always', 'Candle wax', 'Animal fat', 'Wood chips', 'a', 'Exodus 27:20 — "And thou shalt command the children of Israel, that they bring thee pure oil olive beaten for the light, to cause the lamp to burn always."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 27, 'teens', 1, 'What metal covered the altar of burnt offering?', 'Brass (bronze) — the wood was overlaid with brass', 'Gold', 'Silver', 'Copper only', 'a', 'Exodus 27:2 — "And thou shalt make the horns of it upon the four corners thereof... and thou shalt overlay it with brass."'),
('Exodus', 27, 'teens', 2, 'What were the dimensions of the tabernacle courtyard?', 'One hundred cubits long and fifty cubits wide (approximately 150 feet by 75 feet)', 'Ten cubits by ten cubits', 'A thousand cubits by a thousand cubits', 'Fifty cubits by fifty cubits', 'a', 'Exodus 27:18 — "The length of the court shall be an hundred cubits, and the breadth fifty every where."'),
('Exodus', 27, 'teens', 3, 'What was special about the gate to the courtyard?', 'A hanging of blue, purple, scarlet, and fine twined linen — twenty cubits wide, the only entrance to the courtyard', 'There were four gates', 'It was made of gold', 'There was no gate at all', 'a', 'Exodus 27:16 — "And for the gate of the court shall be an hanging of twenty cubits, of blue, and purple, and scarlet, and fine twined linen, wrought with needlework."'),
('Exodus', 27, 'teens', 4, 'What held the courtyard curtains in place?', 'Pillars of brass with silver hooks and silver fillets (bands), set in sockets of brass', 'Wooden poles', 'Stone columns', 'Gold rods', 'a', 'Exodus 27:10-11 — "And the twenty pillars thereof and their twenty sockets shall be of brass; the hooks of the pillars and their fillets shall be of silver."'),
('Exodus', 27, 'teens', 5, 'When was the lamp to burn in the tabernacle?', 'From evening to morning — Aaron and his sons were to keep it burning continuously before the LORD', 'Only on the Sabbath', 'Only during sacrifices', 'Only at noon', 'a', 'Exodus 27:21 — "Aaron and his sons shall order it from evening to morning before the LORD: it shall be a statute for ever."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 27, 'adults', 1, 'What is the theological significance of the brazen altar being the first object encountered?', 'It establishes that the only way to approach God is through sacrifice — before entering God''s presence, sin must be dealt with at the altar; this physical arrangement teaches that atonement precedes fellowship, pointing to Christ''s sacrifice as the prerequisite for approaching God', 'The altar placement was arbitrary', 'The altar was unimportant', 'Fellowship preceded sacrifice', 'a', 'The altar of burnt offering stands between the gate and the tabernacle — no one passes to God''s presence without first encountering the place of sacrifice. This spatial theology teaches: access to God requires atonement. Hebrews 13:10: "We have an altar."'),
('Exodus', 27, 'adults', 2, 'Why is the altar overlaid with brass rather than gold or silver?', 'Brass (bronze) represents judgment — it can withstand fire and symbolises God''s righteous judgment against sin; the altar where sin is judged uses the metal of judgment, while the mercy seat (where sin is covered) uses gold (glory and grace)', 'Brass was the cheapest metal', 'Gold would have melted', 'Silver was unavailable', 'a', 'The metal hierarchy in the tabernacle carries theological weight: gold (Holy of Holies — divine glory), silver (sockets — redemption), brass/bronze (outer court — judgment). The brazen altar''s metal matches its function: the place where the fire of judgment falls on substitutionary sacrifice.'),
('Exodus', 27, 'adults', 3, 'How does the single gate to the courtyard point to Christ?', 'There was only one way into the tabernacle courtyard — one entrance, one gate; Jesus declares "I am the door" (John 10:9) and "I am the way" (John 14:6); the singular entrance teaches that there is one way to God, not many', 'There were multiple gates', 'The gate was irrelevant', 'Anyone could enter from any side', 'a', 'Exodus 27:16 — One gate on the east side. This singularity of access echoes throughout Scripture: one way (John 14:6), one door (John 10:9), one mediator (1 Timothy 2:5). The tabernacle''s architecture preaches the exclusivity of the gospel.'),
('Exodus', 27, 'adults', 4, 'What does the perpetual lamp (ner tamid) symbolise?', 'The continuously burning lamp represents God''s constant presence and the perpetual need for spiritual illumination — it must never go out, just as God''s light never ceases; it also symbolises Israel''s calling to be a light to the nations', 'It was merely practical lighting', 'It burned only occasionally', 'It had no symbolic meaning', 'a', 'Exodus 27:20-21 — "To cause the lamp to burn always (tamid — continually)." The perpetual flame represents God''s unceasing presence and faithfulness. It also reflects God''s command to Israel: "Ye are the light of the world" (Matthew 5:14).'),
('Exodus', 27, 'adults', 5, 'How does the white linen of the courtyard fence symbolise righteousness?', 'Fine white linen (shesh) consistently represents righteousness in Scripture — Revelation 19:8 states "fine linen is the righteousness of saints"; the white curtain wall separating holy space from the camp pictures the barrier of righteousness that surrounds God''s presence', 'White linen was cheapest', 'The colour was random', 'Linen had no symbolism', 'a', 'Exodus 27:9 — "Fine twined linen" forms the courtyard wall. The whiteness represents purity and righteousness — a visual boundary declaring that only the righteous may approach God. Revelation 19:8: "The fine linen is the righteousness of saints."'),
('Exodus', 27, 'adults', 6, 'What is the significance of the courtyard being open to the sky?', 'The uncovered courtyard means the altar of sacrifice is exposed to heaven — nothing comes between the sacrifice and God; the smoke of the burnt offering ascends directly to God, and God looks down directly upon the offering', 'It was too difficult to cover', 'Roofing materials were unavailable', 'The design was flawed', 'a', 'The open-air courtyard allows sacrificial smoke to ascend directly to heaven — a "sweet savour unto the LORD" (Leviticus 1:9). The unobstructed vertical connection between altar and heaven pictures the directness of atonement reaching God.'),
('Exodus', 27, 'adults', 7, 'How do the horns of the altar function both practically and symbolically?', 'Practically, they held the sacrifice in place with cords; symbolically, horns represent power and authority — blood was applied to the horns on the Day of Atonement (Leviticus 16:18), and fugitives could grasp them for asylum (1 Kings 1:50)', 'They were purely decorative', 'They had no function', 'They were later removed', 'a', 'Exodus 27:2 — "Thou shalt make the horns of it upon the four corners." Horns (qarnot) symbolise power (Psalm 75:10, 1 Samuel 2:1). Blood on the horns consecrates the altar''s authority. Grasping the horns claimed God''s protection (1 Kings 1:50, 2:28).'),
('Exodus', 27, 'adults', 8, 'Why does the command for the lamp oil (27:20-21) appear in the construction narrative rather than the priestly instructions?', 'It connects the tabernacle''s physical construction with its ongoing worship — the lamp bridges building and service; the community''s responsibility to provide oil teaches that maintaining God''s light requires ongoing, sacrificial participation from all God''s people, not just the priests', 'It was misplaced by editors', 'It was a late addition', 'It belongs in Leviticus', 'a', 'Exodus 27:20-21 — The oil command within the construction narrative links building and worship: the tabernacle is not merely built and admired but actively maintained by the community. The beaten olive oil (pressed, not ground) represents costly, refined worship.');

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 28 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 28, 'kids', 1, 'Who did God choose to be the first high priest?', 'Aaron, Moses'' brother — along with his sons Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar', 'Moses', 'Joshua', 'Caleb', 'a', 'Exodus 28:1 — "And take thou unto thee Aaron thy brother, and his sons with him... that he may minister unto me in the priest''s office."'),
('Exodus', 28, 'kids', 2, 'What did the high priest wear on his chest?', 'A breastplate with twelve beautiful gemstones — one for each of the twelve tribes of Israel', 'A golden shield', 'A silver medal', 'A leather belt', 'a', 'Exodus 28:17,21 — "And thou shalt set in it settings of stones, even four rows of stones... And the stones shall be with the names of the children of Israel, twelve."'),
('Exodus', 28, 'kids', 3, 'What was written on the gold plate on Aaron''s forehead?', '"HOLINESS TO THE LORD"', '"King of Israel"', '"High Priest"', '"God is great"', 'a', 'Exodus 28:36 — "And thou shalt make a plate of pure gold, and grave upon it, like the engravings of a signet, HOLINESS TO THE LORD."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 28, 'teens', 1, 'What was the ephod and what was it made of?', 'A sacred apron-like garment of gold, blue, purple, scarlet, and fine linen worn over the priest''s robe', 'A simple white coat', 'A leather tunic', 'A wool blanket', 'a', 'Exodus 28:6 — "And they shall make the ephod of gold, of blue, and of purple, of scarlet, and fine twined linen, with cunning work."'),
('Exodus', 28, 'teens', 2, 'What two stones were on the shoulders of the ephod?', 'Two onyx stones engraved with the names of the twelve tribes of Israel — six names on each stone', 'Two diamonds', 'Two rubies', 'Two pearls', 'a', 'Exodus 28:9-10 — "And thou shalt take two onyx stones, and grave on them the names of the children of Israel: Six of their names on one stone, and the other six names of the rest on the other stone."'),
('Exodus', 28, 'teens', 3, 'What were the Urim and Thummim?', 'Objects placed in the breastplate of judgment used to determine God''s will — they helped the high priest discern God''s answers', 'Musical instruments', 'Two golden rings', 'Prayer scrolls', 'a', 'Exodus 28:30 — "And thou shalt put in the breastplate of judgment the Urim and the Thummim; and they shall be upon Aaron''s heart, when he goeth in before the LORD."'),
('Exodus', 28, 'teens', 4, 'What was attached to the hem of the high priest''s blue robe?', 'Golden bells alternating with pomegranates of blue, purple, and scarlet — so his sound would be heard when he entered the Holy Place', 'Silver chains', 'Feathers', 'Ribbons', 'a', 'Exodus 28:33-34 — "And beneath upon the hem of it thou shalt make pomegranates of blue, and of purple, and of scarlet... and bells of gold between them round about."'),
('Exodus', 28, 'teens', 5, 'Why were the priestly garments made "for glory and for beauty"?', 'Because the priest represented God before the people and the people before God — his garments reflected God''s glory and the beauty of holiness', 'To impress foreign visitors', 'To compete with Egyptian priests', 'For comfort in the desert heat', 'a', 'Exodus 28:2 — "And thou shalt make holy garments for Aaron thy brother for glory and for beauty."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 28, 'adults', 1, 'How does the high priest bearing Israel''s names on his shoulders and heart picture Christ''s intercession?', 'The shoulder stones (strength) and breastplate (affection) mean the high priest carried Israel before God with both power and love — Christ bears His people before the Father with almighty strength and intimate compassion (Hebrews 7:25)', 'The stones were decorative only', 'Only the breastplate mattered', 'Christ does not intercede', 'a', 'Exodus 28:12,29 — "Aaron shall bear their names before the LORD upon his two shoulders for a memorial" and "upon his heart, when he goeth in before the LORD." Christ our High Priest bears us before God on His shoulders (power) and over His heart (love).'),
('Exodus', 28, 'adults', 2, 'What does "HOLINESS TO THE LORD" on the high priest''s forehead signify?', 'The high priest''s mind and identity are wholly consecrated to God — this golden plate (tzitz) sanctifies the people''s offerings by bearing "the iniquity of the holy things" (28:38), making imperfect worship acceptable through the priest''s mediatorial holiness', 'It was a title of rank', 'It was for identification only', 'All Israelites wore one', 'a', 'Exodus 28:36,38 — "HOLINESS TO THE LORD... Aaron may bear the iniquity of the holy things, which the children of Israel shall hallow... that they may be accepted before the LORD." Even Israel''s worship needed atonement — the golden plate sanctified imperfect offerings.'),
('Exodus', 28, 'adults', 3, 'Why must the bells sound when the high priest enters the Holy Place?', 'So "that he die not" — the sound confirmed the priest was alive and moving (serving) before God; silence might indicate death in God''s presence; the bells also announced intercession, letting the people know their representative was ministering before God', 'For musical accompaniment', 'To wake up the congregation', 'For a pleasant atmosphere', 'a', 'Exodus 28:35 — "And it shall be upon Aaron to minister: and his sound shall be heard when he goeth in unto the holy place before the LORD, and when he cometh out, that he die not." The connection between bells and survival underscores the mortal danger of approaching holy God unworthily.'),
('Exodus', 28, 'adults', 4, 'How do the Urim and Thummim function in Israel''s governance?', 'They provided divine guidance for national decisions — literally "lights and perfections," they gave yes/no or guilty/innocent answers through a process not fully described; they represent God''s direct governance of Israel through the priesthood', 'They were fortune-telling devices', 'They were never actually used', 'They were identical to pagan oracles', 'a', 'Exodus 28:30 — Urim and Thummim (perhaps related to ''light'' and ''completeness/truth'') were the divinely appointed means for discerning God''s will in national matters (Numbers 27:21, 1 Samuel 28:6). They ceased after the exile (Ezra 2:63).'),
('Exodus', 28, 'adults', 5, 'What is the significance of the pomegranate motif on the priestly robe?', 'Pomegranates symbolise fruitfulness, abundance, and the covenant blessings of the Promised Land (Deuteronomy 8:8) — alternating with bells, they combine silent fruitfulness with audible proclamation, suggesting that priestly ministry produces both visible fruit and heard testimony', 'Pomegranates were Aaron''s favourite fruit', 'They were purely decorative', 'They had no symbolic meaning', 'a', 'The pomegranate was one of the seven species of Israel (Deuteronomy 8:8) and appears in Song of Solomon as a symbol of beauty and fruitfulness. Its many seeds within one fruit may also symbolise the unity and diversity of Israel.'),
('Exodus', 28, 'adults', 6, 'How does the priestly wardrobe function as a "wearable theology"?', 'Each garment teaches doctrine: the white linen undergarment (righteousness), blue robe (heavenly calling), ephod (priestly service), breastplate (intercessory love), shoulder stones (bearing God''s people), golden plate (holiness), bells and pomegranates (proclamation and fruitfulness)', 'The garments were standard uniforms', 'Each garment had only practical use', 'The theology was imposed later', 'a', 'Exodus 28:2 — "For glory and for beauty." Every component is theological: the priest''s body becomes a living lesson in how God relates to His people — carried in love, represented before God, sanctified for service. The garments make invisible spiritual realities visible.'),
('Exodus', 28, 'adults', 7, 'What does the breastplate of judgment (choshen mishpat) teach about the priest''s judicial role?', 'The breastplate combined intercession (carrying names before God) with judgment (the Urim and Thummim for divine verdicts) — the priest was not merely a ritual performer but a mediator of divine justice and communication', 'The breastplate was purely ornamental', 'Only Moses judged', 'The priest had no judicial function', 'a', 'Exodus 28:15,30 — The choshen mishpat ("breastplate of judgment") held the Urim and Thummim — tools of divine verdict. This combines the priestly functions of intercession (carrying names) and adjudication (determining God''s will), making the priest both advocate and judge''s representative.'),
('Exodus', 28, 'adults', 8, 'How does the command "that he die not" (28:35,43) establish the gravity of priestly service?', 'The repeated death warning shows that approaching God is inherently dangerous for sinful humans — even the authorized priest in prescribed garments faces death if he violates protocols; this sober reality underscores God''s holiness and the seriousness of worship', 'The warning was not serious', 'Death was never a real risk', 'Only symbolic death was meant', 'a', 'Exodus 28:35,43 — "That he die not" is the refrain of priestly legislation. Nadab and Abihu later die for offering "strange fire" (Leviticus 10:1-2), proving the warning is literal. This gravity makes Christ''s access to God''s presence all the more remarkable.');

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 29 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 29, 'kids', 1, 'What ceremony was performed to make Aaron and his sons priests?', 'They were washed, dressed in the holy garments, and anointed with oil — and animal sacrifices were offered', 'They took a written test', 'They ran a race', 'They built a house', 'a', 'Exodus 29:4-7 — "And Aaron and his sons thou shalt bring unto the door of the tabernacle... and shalt wash them with water. And thou shalt take the garments, and put upon Aaron... and anoint him."'),
('Exodus', 29, 'kids', 2, 'How many days did the consecration ceremony last?', 'Seven days', 'One day', 'Three days', 'Thirty days', 'a', 'Exodus 29:35 — "And thus shalt thou do unto Aaron, and to his sons, according to all things which I have commanded thee: seven days shalt thou consecrate them."'),
('Exodus', 29, 'kids', 3, 'What did God promise at the end of this chapter?', '"I will dwell among the children of Israel, and will be their God"', '"I will give them gold"', '"I will make them kings"', '"I will build them a city"', 'a', 'Exodus 29:45 — "And I will dwell among the children of Israel, and will be their God."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 29, 'teens', 1, 'What three animals were sacrificed during the consecration?', 'One young bull (sin offering) and two rams (one for burnt offering, one for consecration)', 'Three lambs', 'Two goats and a dove', 'One ox and one sheep', 'a', 'Exodus 29:1 — "And this is the thing that thou shalt do unto them to hallow them, to minister unto me in the priest''s office: Take one young bullock, and two rams without blemish."'),
('Exodus', 29, 'teens', 2, 'Where was blood applied to Aaron and his sons during consecration?', 'On the tip of the right ear, the thumb of the right hand, and the great toe of the right foot', 'On their foreheads', 'On their backs', 'On their left hands', 'a', 'Exodus 29:20 — "Then shalt thou kill the ram, and take of his blood, and put it upon the tip of the right ear of Aaron... and upon the thumb of their right hand, and upon the great toe of their right foot."'),
('Exodus', 29, 'teens', 3, 'What was the daily continual offering?', 'Two lambs — one in the morning and one at evening — offered every single day as a continual burnt offering', 'One lamb per week', 'One bull per month', 'Grain only on special occasions', 'a', 'Exodus 29:38-39 — "Now this is that which thou shalt offer upon the altar; two lambs of the first year day by day continually. The one lamb thou shalt offer in the morning; and the other lamb thou shalt offer at even."'),
('Exodus', 29, 'teens', 4, 'What does "a sweet savour" mean when describing the burnt offering?', 'It means the sacrifice was pleasing and acceptable to God — not that God enjoyed the smell, but that the obedient worship was accepted', 'God literally smelled the smoke', 'The meat was well-cooked', 'The spices smelled good', 'a', 'Exodus 29:18 — "It is a burnt offering unto the LORD: it is a sweet savour, an offering made by fire unto the LORD." The Hebrew reach nichoach ("soothing aroma") indicates God''s acceptance of the offering.'),
('Exodus', 29, 'teens', 5, 'What was the "ram of consecration" and why was it special?', 'It was the second ram — its blood consecrated the priests'' ears (to hear God), hands (to serve God), and feet (to walk with God)', 'It was an ordinary sacrifice', 'It was offered only for sin', 'It was burned outside the camp', 'a', 'Exodus 29:19-22 — The ram of consecration (eil millu''im) sanctified the priests'' whole being: ear (hearing), hand (doing), foot (walking) — representing total dedication to God''s service.'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 29, 'adults', 1, 'How does the blood on the ear, thumb, and toe symbolise total consecration?', 'Ear represents hearing God''s word (obedience), thumb represents doing God''s work (service), toe represents walking in God''s ways (conduct) — the blood sanctifies the priest''s entire life: what he hears, does, and where he goes', 'It was a random ceremonial act', 'Only the ear mattered', 'The application was medicinal', 'a', 'Exodus 29:20 — Blood on the extremities consecrates the whole person from head (ear) to hand (action) to foot (direction). This holistic consecration teaches that priesthood — and by extension, Christian life (1 Peter 2:9) — involves total dedication of every faculty.'),
('Exodus', 29, 'adults', 2, 'What does the seven-day consecration period signify?', 'Seven represents completeness — the consecration must run the full course of creation''s week, symbolising that priestly preparation cannot be rushed or abbreviated; thorough sanctification precedes effective ministry', 'Seven was an arbitrary number', 'The ceremony could be shortened', 'It was merely practical timing', 'a', 'Exodus 29:35 — Seven days mirrors the creation week: just as God completed creation in seven days, priestly consecration requires a complete cycle. This teaches that preparation for ministry is not instantaneous but requires a full season of sanctification.'),
('Exodus', 29, 'adults', 3, 'How does the daily burnt offering (tamid) point to Christ?', 'The perpetual morning and evening sacrifice provided a continuous atonement covering for Israel — Christ''s once-for-all sacrifice replaces this need: "by one offering he hath perfected for ever them that are sanctified" (Hebrews 10:14)', 'The daily offering has no Christological significance', 'Christ''s sacrifice was merely another offering', 'The tamid continues today', 'a', 'Exodus 29:38-42 — The tamid sacrifice was offered every day without interruption. Jesus died at 3 PM (the hour of the evening tamid sacrifice — Mark 15:34-37), and His cry "It is finished" (John 19:30) ended the need for perpetual sacrifice.'),
('Exodus', 29, 'adults', 4, 'What is the theological climax of the chapter in verses 45-46?', '"I will dwell among the children of Israel, and will be their God. And they shall know that I am the LORD their God, that brought them forth out of the land of Egypt, that I may dwell among them" — dwelling with God is the purpose of the entire exodus and tabernacle', 'The climax is about the priests', 'The climax is about the sacrifices', 'There is no theological climax', 'a', 'Exodus 29:45-46 — The tabernacle instructions culminate not in a building or ritual but in relationship: "that I may dwell among them." The purpose of redemption, law, priesthood, and sacrifice is all one thing: God''s presence with His people.'),
('Exodus', 29, 'adults', 5, 'How does the wave offering (tenufah) of the breast and the heave offering (terumah) of the thigh function?', 'The wave offering was moved horizontally (north-south-east-west before God) and the heave offering lifted vertically — together they consecrate the offering in all directions, symbolising complete dedication to God while providing the priests'' food', 'They were identical movements', 'Only one was performed', 'These terms are synonymous', 'a', 'Exodus 29:24,27 — The wave breast (tenufah — horizontal presentation) and heave shoulder (terumah — vertical lifting) combine to present the offering comprehensively to God. The movements may represent offering to God (vertical) and before the congregation (horizontal).'),
('Exodus', 29, 'adults', 6, 'What does the anointing oil poured on Aaron''s head represent?', 'The oil symbolises the Holy Spirit''s empowerment for service — just as oil was poured on Aaron (Psalm 133:2), so Christ (Messiah — "Anointed One") was anointed with the Spirit without measure (John 3:34), and believers receive the Spirit''s anointing (1 John 2:20)', 'Oil was a common cosmetic', 'It was purely ceremonial', 'Oil had no spiritual significance', 'a', 'Exodus 29:7 — "Then shalt thou take the anointing oil, and pour it upon his head, and anoint him." The Hebrew mashach (to anoint) gives us Mashiach (Messiah) and Greek Christos (Christ). Aaron''s anointing prefigures Christ''s reception of the Spirit at baptism.'),
('Exodus', 29, 'adults', 7, 'How does the bull as a sin offering (29:10-14) differ from the ram as a burnt offering (29:15-18)?', 'The sin offering (chattath) addresses guilt and atonement — its flesh is burned outside the camp; the burnt offering (olah) expresses total dedication — it is entirely consumed on the altar as a "sweet savour"; together they cover both the negative (removing sin) and positive (offering self) aspects of consecration', 'They served the same purpose', 'Only the sin offering was needed', 'The burnt offering dealt with sin', 'a', 'The sin offering (bull) removes guilt; the burnt offering (ram) dedicates the whole person. Together they teach that priesthood requires both cleansing from sin and complete self-offering — a pattern fulfilled in Christ who is both sin-bearer (2 Corinthians 5:21) and self-offering (Ephesians 5:2).'),
('Exodus', 29, 'adults', 8, 'What is the significance of "I will meet with the children of Israel" at the tabernacle door (29:43)?', 'The tabernacle becomes the designated meeting point between heaven and earth — God commits to a specific location of encounter, making His presence accessible rather than arbitrary; this "theology of meeting" culminates in Christ as the meeting place between God and humanity', 'God could only be found at the tabernacle', 'The meeting was infrequent', 'Only Moses could meet God there', 'a', 'Exodus 29:42-43 — "At the door of the tabernacle of the congregation before the LORD: where I will meet you, to speak there unto thee." God appoints a meeting place — He does not leave encounter to chance but commits to specific, accessible, regular engagement.');

-- ═══ Exodus Chapter 30 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Exodus', 30, 'kids', 1, 'What special small altar was placed inside the tabernacle?', 'The altar of incense — a small gold-covered altar where sweet-smelling incense was burned every morning and evening', 'A cooking stove', 'A bread oven', 'A flower stand', 'a', 'Exodus 30:1,6 — "And thou shalt make an altar to burn incense upon: of shittim wood shalt thou make it... And thou shalt put it before the vail."'),
('Exodus', 30, 'kids', 2, 'What did every Israelite have to pay when they were counted?', 'Half a shekel of silver — the same amount for rich and poor alike', 'One gold coin', 'Five sheep', 'Whatever they wanted', 'a', 'Exodus 30:13,15 — "This they shall give... half a shekel... The rich shall not give more, and the poor shall not give less than half a shekel."'),
('Exodus', 30, 'kids', 3, 'What did the priests wash their hands and feet in before serving?', 'A bronze laver (basin) filled with water, placed between the tabernacle and the altar', 'A golden bowl', 'The river nearby', 'A pot of oil', 'a', 'Exodus 30:18-19 — "Thou shalt also make a laver of brass... and thou shalt put water therein. For Aaron and his sons shall wash their hands and their feet thereat."'),
-- Teens
('Exodus', 30, 'teens', 1, 'When was incense burned on the golden altar?', 'Every morning when Aaron tended the lamps and every evening when he lit the lamps — a perpetual incense before the LORD', 'Only on the Sabbath', 'Once a year on the Day of Atonement', 'Only when they felt like it', 'a', 'Exodus 30:7-8 — "And Aaron shall burn thereon sweet incense every morning: when he dresseth the lamps, he shall burn incense upon it. And when Aaron lighteth the lamps at even, he shall burn incense upon it, a perpetual incense before the LORD."'),
('Exodus', 30, 'teens', 2, 'Why was the half-shekel called "ransom money" (atonement money)?', 'It was a ransom for each person''s soul — acknowledging that every life belongs to God and must be redeemed; it prevented plague when the people were numbered', 'It was a tax for the army', 'It paid for the priests'' food', 'It was a membership fee', 'a', 'Exodus 30:12,16 — "When thou takest the sum of the children of Israel... then shall they give every man a ransom for his soul unto the LORD... that there be no plague among them."'),
('Exodus', 30, 'teens', 3, 'What were the special ingredients of the holy anointing oil?', 'Pure myrrh, sweet cinnamon, sweet calamus, cassia, and olive oil — a sacred blend not to be copied for personal use', 'Any common oil would do', 'Water and honey', 'Crushed flowers only', 'a', 'Exodus 30:23-25 — "Take thou also unto thee principal spices, of pure myrrh five hundred shekels, and of sweet cinnamon half so much... and of cassia five hundred shekels... and of oil olive an hin."'),
('Exodus', 30, 'teens', 4, 'What happened to anyone who made a copy of the holy anointing oil or incense?', 'They would be cut off from their people — these sacred recipes were reserved exclusively for tabernacle use', 'They were fined', 'They had to serve as priests', 'Nothing happened', 'a', 'Exodus 30:33,38 — "Whosoever compoundeth any like it, or whosoever putteth any of it upon a stranger, shall even be cut off from his people."'),
('Exodus', 30, 'teens', 5, 'What would happen if the priests did not wash at the laver before entering the tabernacle?', 'They would die — "they shall wash with water, that they die not"', 'They would get a warning', 'They would be fined', 'Nothing serious', 'a', 'Exodus 30:20-21 — "When they go into the tabernacle of the congregation, they shall wash with water, that they die not."'),
-- Adults
('Exodus', 30, 'adults', 1, 'How does the altar of incense represent prayer in Scripture?', 'Psalm 141:2 explicitly connects incense with prayer: "Let my prayer be set forth before thee as incense." Revelation 5:8 and 8:3-4 identify the golden bowls of incense as "the prayers of saints" — the altar of incense makes prayer visible and aromatic, ascending to God', 'Incense had no connection to prayer', 'Only the burnt offering represented prayer', 'Incense was purely atmospheric', 'a', 'Exodus 30:1-8, Psalm 141:2, Revelation 8:3-4 — The incense altar stood before the veil (closest to God''s presence), and its perpetual burning parallels perpetual prayer (1 Thessalonians 5:17). Luke 1:10 confirms: "the whole multitude of the people were praying without at the time of incense."'),
('Exodus', 30, 'adults', 2, 'What does the equal half-shekel for rich and poor teach about atonement?', 'Every soul has equal value before God — no one can buy more atonement with greater wealth, and no one is excused by poverty; the uniform price teaches that all stand equally in need of redemption and all are equally valued by God', 'The wealthy should pay more', 'The poor were exempt', 'Atonement cost varied by tribe', 'a', 'Exodus 30:15 — "The rich shall not give more, and the poor shall not give less than half a shekel." Before God, social and economic distinctions vanish — each soul costs the same to redeem. This democratisation of atonement anticipates the gospel''s universal offer.'),
('Exodus', 30, 'adults', 3, 'How does the laver (bronze basin) picture sanctification?', 'The laver provides ongoing cleansing for those already consecrated — positioned between the altar (justification) and the tabernacle (service), it teaches that initial forgiveness must be followed by continual purification; this parallels Jesus washing the disciples'' feet (John 13:10)', 'The laver was for drinking water', 'It had no spiritual significance', 'Only the altar mattered', 'a', 'Exodus 30:18-21 — The laver''s position between altar and tent is theologically significant: after sacrifice (atonement) comes washing (sanctification) before service (ministry). Jesus said to Peter: "He that is washed needeth not save to wash his feet" (John 13:10) — believers need ongoing cleansing.'),
('Exodus', 30, 'adults', 4, 'What does the prohibition against replicating the holy anointing oil teach?', 'Sacred things must not be profaned by common use — the oil set apart for God''s service cannot be appropriated for human purposes; this principle of separation between holy and common undergirds all biblical holiness and teaches that God''s things are God''s alone', 'The recipe was copyrighted', 'The ingredients were poisonous', 'It was an economic regulation', 'a', 'Exodus 30:32-33 — "Upon man''s flesh shall it not be poured, neither shall ye make any other like it." The holy-common distinction is fundamental to biblical theology: what God consecrates for His purposes must not be domesticated for human use (cf. Leviticus 10:10).'),
('Exodus', 30, 'adults', 5, 'How does the census ransom money connect to Peter''s doctrine of redemption?', 'Peter writes that believers are "not redeemed with corruptible things, as silver and gold... But with the precious blood of Christ" (1 Peter 1:18-19) — the half-shekel ransomed life temporarily; Christ''s blood ransoms eternally, fulfilling and surpassing the census payment', 'Peter never addresses redemption', 'The ransom was sufficient forever', 'There is no connection', 'a', '1 Peter 1:18-19 — "Forasmuch as ye know that ye were not redeemed with corruptible things, as silver and gold... But with the precious blood of Christ, as of a lamb without blemish and without spot." The half-shekel was a pointer to the ultimate ransom.'),
('Exodus', 30, 'adults', 6, 'What is the theological significance of incense being offered morning and evening?', 'The twice-daily incense creates a perpetual cycle of prayer covering all of Israel''s waking hours — morning and evening frame the day with intercession, teaching that the people live between prayers; this rhythm later shapes synagogue and church liturgical patterns', 'Twice daily was arbitrary', 'Once was sufficient', 'The timing was flexible', 'a', 'Exodus 30:7-8 — Morning and evening incense creates a framework of continual intercession. Daniel prayed three times daily (Daniel 6:10). The Didache (8:3) prescribes the Lord''s Prayer three times. The incense rhythm established structured, regular communion with God.'),
('Exodus', 30, 'adults', 7, 'Why is the altar of incense covered with gold rather than brass like the burnt offering altar?', 'Gold indicates that the incense altar belongs to the sphere of grace (Holy Place) not judgment (outer court) — prayer/intercession occurs in the realm of God''s glory and favour, not at the place of judgment; the metal matches the theological environment', 'Gold was stronger against heat', 'Brass was unavailable inside', 'The choice was aesthetic', 'a', 'Exodus 30:3 — "Thou shalt overlay it with pure gold." The metal progression from brass (court/judgment) to gold (tabernacle/glory) reflects movement from judgment to grace. The incense altar''s gold signals that prayer occurs in the realm of favour, not condemnation.'),
('Exodus', 30, 'adults', 8, 'How does the annual blood application on the incense altar''s horns (30:10) connect the Day of Atonement to daily prayer?', 'Once a year, blood from the sin offering is applied to the golden altar''s horns — linking atonement to intercession; prayer is only effective because atonement has been made; without the blood, even the fragrant incense would be unacceptable to a holy God', 'The blood was merely ceremonial', 'Prayer works independently of atonement', 'The annual application was optional', 'a', 'Exodus 30:10 — "Aaron shall make an atonement upon the horns of it once in a year with the blood of the sin offering of atonements." This annual renewal sanctifies the place of prayer, teaching that prayer''s efficacy depends on the blood of atonement — a principle fulfilled in Hebrews 10:19-22.');
